ce:section.ce:para:
Transmission electron microscope (TEM) is a powerful tool to examine the morphology of nanoscale CDs. As observed in Fig. 2
                           , most CDs have a round or oval shape with slight aggregation. An average diameter of about 20 nm with a rather broad size distribution was determined by the dynamic light scattering (DLS), which are in agreement with the observation from the TEM images. Although the nanoparticles of the CDs are not uniformed in size, good lattice structures presented in the CDs. Such crystalline carbon character was proved by the sharp peaks in the XRD patterns (Fig. 3
                           ), indicative of that a great amount of crystalline graphite exists inside the CDs (Chae et al., 2019).
